title: Evaluated activation cross sections of longer-lived radionuclides produced by deuteron induced reactions on natural iron up to 10 MeV

x4freetext: Evaluated activation cross sections of longer-lived
radionuclides  produced by deuteron induced reactions
on natural iron up to 10 MeV

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Nucl. Instrum. Methods in Physics Res., Sect.B, Vol.267, p.15 (2009)

x4codes.hlp: Institute for Nuclear Research (ATOMKI), Debrecen, Hungary

x4freetext: High purity thin Fe foils as target 7.6 micron and
high purity Ti foils as monitor 4.0 micron.

x4codes.hlp: Institute for Nuclear Research (ATOMKI), Debrecen, Hungary

x4freetext: Stacked target technique was used.
The irradiation was done in a standard target holder.
The beam intensity was deduced from charge measurement
and compared to monitor reactions.
Activity measurements were done without chemical
separation.
The 15 cross section data points measured on Ti foils
fit well to the recommended excitation curve.
The recommended data were taken from the IAEA database.
The incident beam energy was determined from the
parameter settings of the accelerator and was also
checked using the monitor reaction.
No correction was needed.
The mean energy in each foil was calculated on the
basis of the polynomial approximation of Andersen
and Ziegler.

x4codes.shortRef: Book: H.H.Andersen,H Stopping Powers and Ranges,Pergamon 77,  (1977)

x4freetext: Volume 3
The energy degradation as a function of depth in the
stack was determined by calculation.
The uncertainty in the primary beam energy
was estimated to be 0.25 MeV.
Due to the straggling effect and uncertainty of foil
thickness it increased to 0.4 MeV at the last foil in
the stack.
The uncertainty on the measured cross
sections was 11-13%. The following individual
uncertainties are included in the propagated error
(Only the linearly contributing independent error
sources were taken.):
* detection efficiency (5-7%) depending on the energy
of the detected gamma-photon; determination of the
peak areas, including statistical errors (1-5%);
* abundance of the gamma rays analysed (<1%).
foil thickness or the number of target nuclei,
including target non-uniformities (5%);
incident particle intensity (5%);
S.Takacs, 2008.
